This should be close but most likely this will be in the 1 million to 1.3 million range. If there is a delivery blowout, they will break past 1.3 million. Anecdotally, I just went with my mother-in-law to help her pick up a new Model 3 at the local Tesla Service Center, and I saw them absolutely slammed with business. I am not sure the average consumer cares about Elon's crazy antics, so I continue to think that there's a decent shot at breaking past 1.3 million.

Though Berlin and Texas could increase these numbers somewhat going forward, however overall I believe these are still in the ramp up phase so probably won't do numbers comparable to other factories this year.

Increasing bin 3 given that for 1.3M to be reached 375k production required for each of the last two quarters. Obviously growth rates are there and if Shanghai and Berlin come under steam the production will be markably up. Berlin was mentioned to have 1000 rolling and this will be increased. Assume they achieve an average of 2500 per week it gives an additional of 50-100 for the year so with run rates of 290 in q4 and q1 that gives 340, so questioning if the rest from Shanghai will do. They say in the Q2 report that Shanghai was closed for most of Q2 but ended with a record month. The total q2 production vs q1 is -50k, so that then would imply that Shanghai could run(s) at 150k per quarter which is 100k more than now. Therefore I get to 242 (q2 base) +90 (Shanghai delta) +40 (Berlin) = 372 per quarter *2 = 744 +550 (production so far) = 1294k, which would just be bin 3.

Simple extrapolation based on quarterly growth so far places Tesla at 1.8 million, which seems very high. On the other hand, they seem to track to meet their ambitious target of 50% production growth in 2021. An additional 50% growth in 2022, which is what at least one analyst is predicting (https://electrek.co/2021/09/17/tesla-tsla-reach-million-deliveries-2022/), would get production to 1.3 million. Taking the average of the two gives 1.5 million, which is my mean estimate for now. Left significant normally distributed spread to reflect uncertainty. I assumed a production below 2021 levels is quite unlikely, which meant I put most of my estimate above 900,000.

Looks like Tesla is on track to double delivery of cars from 2020 to 2021 (from 500k in 2020 to approaching 1M in 2021, https://www.statista.com/statistics/502208/tesla-quarterly-vehicle-deliveries/). Given Musk's ambition, and more and more Governments moving regulations and incentives in favour of green energy and e-vehicles, I see no reason why the trend could not continue. Only concern is global supply chains, especially semiconductors, that could put a spanner in the works.

Since Q3-2020, there has been a growth of 17% in Model 3/Y on average. Initial estimates based on projecting quarterly numbers forward and adjustments made based on rising inflation rates and interest rates for the dollar and euro.

Last three quarters the quarter over quarter 3 and Y growth has ranged from around 10-15%. Projecting 10% growth out through 2022 would put it right at 1.3 million. I think there's an especially good chance of exceeding since Berlin and Texas seem likely to be coming online soon. According to the article linked below both factories are supposed to have 500k annual capacity. I doubt they'll hit that their first year as they ramp up, but maybe another 500k between them. I don't know if I can add that directly to the 1.3 million, because I'm not sure if that 10-15% quarterly growth is due to new capacity opening up or if it's due to increased plant efficiencies or what. But either way, I think there's a fairly strong case for over 1.3 million deliveries.
